1484":"1484","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","23 August 1512":"23 August 1512","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England","Richmond, Yorkshire, England":"Richmond, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Aske","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Staffordshire): topographic name from northern Middle English <i>ask</i> ‘ash tree’ (Old Norse <i>askr</i>), or a habitational name from Aske (North Yorkshire). Compare   Ash  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ash","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>asche</i> ‘ash tree’ (Old English <i>æsc</i>), hence a topographic name for someone living by an ash tree or a habitational name from any of the many places in southern and central England named with this word (Derbyshire, Dorset, Hampshire, Herefordshire, Kent, Surrey, Shropshire, Somerset, and elsewhere).","Americanized form of German   Asch   and   Esch  , the latter ultimately also of Swiss German origin (see   Oesch  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Dufresne  , with the same meaning as 1 above."]},{"name":"Axe","meanings":["English (West Yorkshire, Lincolnshire): variant of   Aske   with metathesis of /sk/ to /ks/, spelled with an <i>x</i>.","English (Dorset, Somerset): habitational name from Axe Farm in Chardstock (Devon, formerly in Dorset), itself named for the river Axe, which forms part of the south-eastern boundary of Chardstock parish.","Americanized form of German   Axt   or perhaps of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Easby","type":"LAST","meanings":["Eas, genitive of ea, a river, and by, a habitation, meaning habitation of a river, or banks of a river"],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Roger of Easby Aske Esq was born in 1484, in Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England. He married Margaret Place in 1505, in Yorkshire, England. He died on 23 August 1512, in Richmond, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 28, and was buried in Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"1484–23 August 1512":"1484–23. august 1512","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1505–1568":"1505–1568","1484–1512":"1484–1512","1568":"1568","1512":"1512","2 September 1512":"2. september 1512","1484":"1484","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","23 August 1512":"23. august 1512","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England","Richmond, Yorkshire, England":"Richmond, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1484–23 August 1512":"1484–23. elokuuta 1512","1480–Female":"1480–Kuollut","1505–1568":"1505–1568","1484–1512":"1484–1512","1568":"1568","1512":"1512","2 September 1512":"2. syyskuuta 1512","1484":"1484","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","23 August 1512":"23. elokuuta 1512","Y